As I was unconscious, I had a strange dream that I had killed Lani in order to stop her from killing the elephant. When I [[woke up|We were found]] I felt strange as I would never do something like that.
One of the [[businessmen| The men]] handed me and Lani a loaded rifle and I said, "I'm not hunting". The man replied, "You need to take it. You will need it madam." He proceeded to show me how to use the rifle.
In our last breakup Lani called, I could tell she was [[crying|Friendship]] by the sniffing sound she made as she asked me, "Marianna, would you take a trip to Africa with me?" Without a hesitation I joyfully [[accepted her invitation|Apology]], and I did my moonwalk dance as I hung up the phone.
When we [[arrived|Walking Through the Savannah]] at our destination I searched for a trace of fear in Lani's eyes, but I found none.
I turned around and went back to face the [[selfish|Arguments]] [[Lani|TheHuntress]].

I see the giant elephant with his long white tusk running away from the crack of my [[rifle|How the rifle was obtain]]. "Baraag" the elephant screams, running faster as I walk towards my target. Suddenly, the wind begins to blow, and beads of sweat pour over my forehead as the baking sun settles on the horizon. I close my eyes because I know I'm almost there. With a heavy breath I start counting "One, two, three." I slowly open my eyes, let the rifle drop to the ground, and realize that I did it... I let the bullet travel through the green tall grass of [[Tanzania|Village]] and into the smooth red hair of my best friend [[Lani Waggan.|LWDescription]]
Lani was a mean girl, whenever we ate together, she would snatch my food and tell me "You've had enough Marianna." She would close into me whispering, "You're getting too fat to be my [[friend.|Friendship]]" Most of the time I hated her, and because of [[situations|Back to Lani]] like this, we would stop talking for <<cyclinglink "days" "weeks" "months">>.
Eventually, my hope of finding the men started fading away as the bugs kept zapping on my neck and the largeness of the savannah overwhelmed my fear of being [[lonely|The mistake]].
I saw Lani as a huntress ready to [[shoot|The doing]] the innocent animal in front of her.
I yelled at Lani, "Lani the poachers are here duck!" I knew that she was scared of them, so I lied in order to save the elephant. As she turned around listening to what I was saying she accidentally [[knocked|The dream]] me out with her rifle.
As Lani and I were laying on the ground we heard some familiar voices near us. It was the businessmen, and they [[finally|We left]] found us.
I had never seen Lani so happy, so full of life, while on the other hand I had never been so scared. We sat on a roofless 1977 Toyota [[Land|Destination]] Cruiser.
We met with four "businessmen", what hunters call the local men who accompany them, informing us that we had to remain [[close|Walking Through the Savannah]] and be careful because poachers were reported around the area.
Here is the thing, Lani Waggan loved to hunt, and not just any rabbit or deer. She loved to hunt the "Big Five Game" of Africa which included the [[rhino|The creatures]], elephant, lion, leopard, and the Cape buffalo.
I felt relieved that I finally got rid of our bad relationship, no more calling me "fat," and threatening to end our friendship. Shortly after, the businessmen arrived and they were all murmuring, I could tell they looked [[shocked|The questioning]] and scared because they left us unsupervised.
I angrily turned around in search of the local men. I looked back and saw Lani rolling her eyes but quickly settling into her hunting mode. I occasionally skipped just in case there was a snake around ready to launch as I drew further [[away|In Search of the Men]] from Lani.
[[Mr. Waggan|Waggan]], Lani's father, influenced Lani's [[hobby|Huntress]] and obsession when she was a little girl by taking her on his African hunting trips. By the age of 12 Lani killed her first White rhino.
One of the men asked me, "Madam, what happened?" All I could get out was, "the poachers." We all hopped back on the Land cruiser and the men placed Lani's body on the back with a small [[black|darkness]] towel to cover her face.

Awakening in Africa
Lani was so desperate to leave as everyone thought that the poachers were in the area. A group of businessmen and the local police were working together in order to clear the area. After Mr. Waggan was called and told of the situation, he immediately sent his jet to [[fly|The horizon]] us home.
The [[invitation|Breakup]] was more like an apology. It's the only way she knew how to say sorry.
In the end, when we were taking off on the jet, I looked up at the horizon where the last glimpse of light could be seen and\nfrom afar I thought I saw the shadow of the bull elephant. It reminded me how paramount his life is, and that if I hadn't lied his life would have been wasted.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nImage credit: https://pixabay.com/en/africa-savannah-national-park-tree-944465/
I remember Lani proudly showed me a framed picture of a lifeless [[White rhino|First kill]] the first time I went to her house.There were heads with fur and sharp teeth hanging on the walls of the office room as if time had frozen for those innocent creatures.
As soon as she was next to me, she started crying, but I still wanted to tell her "I told you not to post the pictures," and I did. Lani gave me her piercing sad look but I rolled my eyes and [[hugged|The kids]] her trying to provide some consolation. I could smell her Viva La Juicy perfume on her hair.
Everything desirable by a woman, from money to beauty, can be found in Lani Waggan. She had long red hair that made heads turn in the school hallway and her piercing emerald green eyes exempted her from [[trouble.|Arguments]]
Without warning, I leaned my head on top of Lani's body and [[tears|sadness]] consumed my face. I had many mixed [[feelings|Felt]] of what I had just done.

As we stood there hugging, the kids kept calling her names and pushing us on the locker. However, I also wanted to scream at her, for I never [[understood|The hunt]] how she could kill such [[majestic creatures|The creatures]].
I was the only person in the world who would listen to her [[cry|Breakup]] when she had "[[problems|Reaction@School]]" and she was my only friend.
The sunset grew darker and so did my feelings. I started to believe that I actually did the world a [[favor|The end]]. I killed a killing machine, an evil predator, and a manipulative, patronizing, pompous monster.
As the time for our [[trip|Village]] closed in Lani became an abomination at our school. She decided to post [[pictures|The creatures]] on social media of her previous trip to Tanzania, which I had previously managed to convince her not to do so. A picture of her hugging a dead lion, five times her size, as she grinned with a rifle in her hand went [[viral within an hour.|Nextday]]
And I shot [[her|WhathaveIdone]]...

As Lani and I stomped through the grass the businessmen where further and further away until we lost sight of them. I quickly panicked and said, "Lani I think we [[lost them.|In Search of the Men]]" She gave me a [[look of nuisance|Bothered]] and replied, "it's fine, we will find them again, now hush, I want to get me an elephant."
Her dad, Georg Waggan, a CEO of a multibillion-dollar software company provided the Waggan household with a lot of money. Being that Lani was an only child, she was given everything she [[wanted|Breakup]] without having to earn any of it.
